<subSubSection pageId="138" pageNumber="535" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="138.[730,1323,814,1233]" pageId="138" pageNumber="535">Phylogenetic placement of C. mulesae is uncertain but based on 16s rRNA se- quences, it seems to be in the C. olivier: group and might be conspecific with C. olwiert. Monotypic.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="138" pageNumber="535" type="distribution">
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6871793" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6871793" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6871793/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="138" pageNumber="535" targetBox="[116,707,815,1229]" targetPageId="138">
<paragraph blockId="138.[730,1323,814,1233]" pageId="138" pageNumber="535">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[731,907,1082,1115]" pageId="138" pageNumber="535">Distribution.</emphasis>
Recorded from SW Central African Republic, NW DR Congo, and SE 
<taxonomicName box="[732,844,1162,1195]" class="Insecta" family="Acrididae" genus="Uganda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="138" pageNumber="535" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Uganda</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="138" pageNumber="535" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="138.[730,1323,814,1233]" lastBlockId="138.[118,1324,1240,1943]" pageId="138" pageNumber="535">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[731,989,1200,1233]" pageId="138" pageNumber="535">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 115 mm, tail 64 mm, hindfoot 16 mm. No specific data are available for body weight. The Ugandan White-toothed Shrew is a very large, with long pelage. Dorsal and ventral pelage is grayish. Feet are darker grayish, and hindfeet are long and broad. Tail is ¢.60-75% of head-body length, very hairy and covered with tightly packed long bristle hairs, and dark grayish. The Ugandan White-toothed Shrew is similar to the African Giant White-toothed Shrew (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lesson" authorityYear="1827" box="[437,568,1445,1470]" class="Mammalia" family="Soricidae" genus="Sorex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="138" pageNumber="539" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="olivieri">C. olivieri</taxonomicName>
), but it is smaller and has less robust and smaller skull. There are three unicuspids.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="138" pageNumber="535" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="138.[118,1324,1240,1943]" pageId="138" pageNumber="535">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[119,230,1516,1549]" pageId="138" pageNumber="535">Habitat.</emphasis>
Areas with relatively low understories such as unlogged forest. Some Ugandan White-toothed Shrews have been collected in forests dominated by 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J.Leonard" authorityYear="1952" box="[1115,1323,1555,1588]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Gilbertiodendron" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="138" pageNumber="535" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Gilbertiodendron</taxonomicName>
dewevrei (
<taxonomicName box="[246,382,1600,1629]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="138" pageNumber="535" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
